ngdom"},"da":{"1425–":"1425–Afdød","1425–Male":"1425–Afdød","1430–1455":"1430–1455","1454–Male":"1454–Afdød","1400–1463":"1400–1463","1400–1487":"1400–1487","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1487":"1487","1420":"1420","1463":"1463","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","Worcester, , Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","Derby, , Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1425–":"1425–Overleden","1425–Male":"1425–Overleden","1430–1455":"1430–1455","1454–Male":"1454–Overleden","1400–1463":"1400–1463","1400–1487":"1400–1487","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1487":"1487","1420":"1420","1463":"1463","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","Worcester, , Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","Derby, , Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1425–":"1425–Deceased","1425–Male":"1425–Deceased","1430–1455":"1430–1455","1454–Male":"1454–Deceased","1400–1463":"1400–1463","1400–1487":"1400–1487","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1487":"1487","1420":"1420","1463":"1463","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","Worcester, , Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","Derby, , Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jodrell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Jaundrill  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jaundrill","meanings":["Norman, English: nickname from Middle English * <i>jaunerel</i> ( <i>jaune</i> ‘yellow’ + suffix  <i>-erel</i>, of Anglo-Norman origin), for someone with a yellowish complexion, possibly suffering from jaundice. For the  <i>-d-</i>, compare the word  <i>jaundice</i>, from Old French  <i>jaunice</i>. The variant  <i>Jod(e)rell</i> may have arisen through misreading  <i>Jandrell</i> as * <i>Jaudrell</i>. Note William Jawdrell, 1448 in PROB 11, whose name may be an early form of  <i>Jodrell</i> or a misreading of  <i>Jaundrell</i>."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":30,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When George William Jodrell was born in 1425, in Derby, Derbyshire, England, his father, Roger Jodrell II, was 25 and his mother, Matilda Sutton, was 25. He married Joan Asheton in 1450, in Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1425–":"1425–Surnud","1425–Male":"1425–Surnud","1430–1455":"1430–1455","1454–Male":"1454–Surnud","1400–1463":"1400–1463","1400–1487":"1400–1487","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1487":"1487","1420":"1420","1463":"1463","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","Worcester, , Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","Derby, , Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1425–":"1425–Kuollut","1425–Male":"1425–Kuollut","1430–1455":"1430–1455","1454–Male":"1454–Kuollut","1400–1463":"1400–1463","1400–1487":"1400–1487","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1487":"1487","1420":"1420","1463":"1463","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","W